 1> Git cherry pick ?
  
 = it is used to copy a specific commit from one branch to another without
   merging the entrie branch.

  # why do we use cherry pick?
   
   = - to copy a single feature or bug fix.
   
     - to avoid unnecessary commits.
   
     - to move important changes between branches.

  # commands
 
  git log --oneline
  git cherry-pick [commit id]



 2> git stash 
 
 = git stash is used to temporarily save uncommited changes without
   creating a commit .

 # why do we use git stash ?

 - to temporarily save unfinished work.

 - to switch branches without losing changes.

 - to continue work later from the same point.

   # workflow

    work on feature.
  
   save changes using git stash.
  
   switch to another branch.
   
   complete the urgent task.

   return to the original branch.

   restore the saved work using git stash.


 # commands

 git stash = temporarily saves all uncommitted changes and cleans the working directory.
 git stash list = display all saved stashes.
 git stash apply = restore the latest stash without removing it from the stash list.
 git stash pop = restores the latest stash and removes it from the stash list.
 git stash pop stash@{0} = restore specific stash and remove it from stash list.
 git stash drop stash @{0}= delete a soecific stash.
 git stash clear = deletes all saved stashes.




 3> What is Git tag ?

 = git tag is used to assign a permanent name (version) to
   an important commit.

 Example = v1.0 , v2.0



 # why do we use git tag ?
 
 - software versioning.
 - mark stable releases.
 = indentify important commits.

 # commands 
 
 git tag v1.0 = create a new tag named
 git show v1.0 = display information about the v1.0 tag including the commits detail.
 git tag <tag name> <commit-id> = create a tag for a specific commit.
 git tag -d <tag-name> = deletes a local tag .
 git push origin <tag-name> = pushes a specific tag to a github repository
 git push origin --tags = push all local tags
